keep secrets from us

Pitt Police Chief Deborah Furka,

Yesterday, we made a few suggestions about
how your department can improve its service to the
campus community. We forgot something:

Make sure your ofﬁcers don't keep crimes a
secret.

Yesterday afternoon, a man who allegedly tried
to rob the clothes vendor on the comer of Forbes
and Bigelow was arrested in front of the Cathedral.
When a Pitt News reporter tried to photograph and
document the incident, an oﬂicer told him to leave.
Later, the reporter called the Pitt Police for com-
ments, but the ofﬁcer who answered the phone
refused to give any information.

She also refused to give her name.

Chief Furka, please inform your oﬂicers that
they are public servants and, hence, they must be
held accountable to the people of this community.
That responsibility includes open and honest com-
munication with the public.

When ﬂiere are answers that will help the pub-
he become more aware of their safety on this cam-
pus and what is happening around them, we need
to hear those answers.

In addition, an ofﬁcefs refusing to give her
name over the phone is very suspicious. Why was
she afraid to talk about the matter? And if she was
telling the truth about what happened, why was she
afraid to give her name‘? I .

The last time this happened, Pitt football play-
er Kirk McMullen's name was left off an Oakland
crime report. McMullen had punched a student,
breaking his nose, and though state law requires all
adults who are arrested or cited to be identiﬁed in a
public report, McMullen's name was not on that
report. When called for comment and explanation,
the officer who answered reﬁised to give his name,
too.

Police wear numbered badges so they can be
identiﬁed and held accountable. They are, after all,

-public servants. As the public, we must be able to

verify that our protectors are doing ﬂieir job. When
an officer hides her identity, that makes us wonder
what else she is hiding.

Ours is not a police state. We're supposed to
respect our authorities because we trust them. They
have to trust us, too. They can start by being open
about crimes.

After all, only criminals cover up criminal
activity.

 
  

