THE PITT NEWS

Smoke or quit, but don't
just talk about quitting

Adam

Schaible

The mechanics of addiction is an
increasingly popular topic of discussion
these days, and is now an area of expertise
for many physicians and psychologists.
And everyone from major pharmaceutical
companies down to hypnotists and self-
help authors makes big money trying to
help people conquer their dependencies.

Brad Swink's three-part series on
smoking focused on the dynamics of nico-

tine addiction on the Pitt
campus, featuring
numerous students

enslaved, one milligram
at a time, to that color-
less, odorless substance.
Even if you don't smoke,
you may know some of
the students in the series
or someone else close to
you who has the nicotine
habit. I've personally
been on both sides of the
coin. As an ex-smoker
who started (like many
others) in college in
1995 and has been
smoke-free since 
February 1997, I know both the euphoria
and the dull, monotonous terror that nico-
tine addiction brings. -

I've exorcised cigarettes so completely
from my life that even a whiff of second-
hand smoke from passersby on the street
will sometimes cause me to convulse in
ﬁts of wheezing and coughing.

- When I strike up a conversation with a
smoker, whether it's a friend or just a casu-
al acquaintance, he'll notice my little
paroxysm of hacking and ask me if I want
him to put it out. I always decline, partly
because I feel that smokers are already dis-
criminated against enough by society that
there's no need for me to add to their dis-
grace. Smokers are, without a doubt, the
closest thing modern society has to a pan-
ah class. I remember standing among the
untouchables on many a sub—zero after-
noon if my craving was bad enough. All of
the anti—smoking efforts and propaganda
that are the tools of the government and
private foundations only add to the indig-
nity. While these efforts have good inten-
tions at heart, they often serve only to fur-
ther the feelings of anger and alienation
among more dedicated smokers.

Truth be told, if you are going to quit
smoking, no government, public service
message, pill, patch, hypnotist or chewing
gum can do it for you. You have to stop it
yourself. For the hardened smoker, per-
haps a 12-step program may be of some
use. My own approach to ending my nico-
tine addiction involved a time of personal
ﬁnancial hardship when I was unable even
to aﬁord a single pack of Marlboros.

He said

Fortunately, I was able to ﬁnd recourse in

two large bottles of aspirin and Jim Beam '

to take the edge off the withdrawal
headache that racked my cranium for two
weeks. Though I relapsed a couple times,
the worst was over; the craving was gone.

Some addicts may rationalize or talk
down their addiction, using classic lines
like "I can quit anytime," "Actually, I'm

cutting down," or "I switched to lights." I

These people are just as weak and indeci-
sive as hardcore, lifetime smokers. You
know you have a problem, you think
something needs to be
done, so why do it half-
assed? And if you can
quit anytime, why not
after the next time you
crush a butt in an ash-
tray or let it sparkle on
the ground outside the
window of your speed-
ing car? It's one thing to
be weak, but to
acknowledge this
weakness and even
revel in it is truly self-
destructive.

The problem
with a lot of Americans
nowadays is that they're
either all talk, no action, or they allow
themselves to be beaten down by forces
beyond their control. Be strong; rise up. By
acknowledging your weakness and elimi-
nating it, you can start a string of positive
events that can change your life forever. I
know it, because I've lived it.

l‘."" ,- of the people in Swink's series
mention how nicotine addiction has turned
them into "slaves." They aren't just slaves
of nicotine. By extension, addicts are
slaves of the cigarette companies, who
reap fabulous proﬁts; of the government,
whose politicians see smokers‘ addictions
as an endless source of tax revenue; and of
the medical ﬁeld, which will be busy for
many generations to come trying to keep
smokers alive long enough to know their
grandchildren.

By quitting smoking, 1 resumed a
small but important degree of control over
my own life. Now, no one likes a control
freak. I'm man enough to admit many
things are beyond my control: the car that
breaks down on the Parkway, the girl who
doesn't call back after the ﬁrst date, or the
roommate who has no regard for any sense
of cleanliness or propriety. But those who
refuse to take control of a situation like

_ nicotine addiction, one that is well within

the grasp of any modern, educated citizen,
especially those of us smart enough to
attend an institution like Pitt, are not only
weak but irresponsible as well. 4

Adam Schaible will try to convince himself
tonight over a bottle of his favorite dark
Australian stout that he's not a hypocrite.

 

