hockey trouble

One night, I sat down in a chair
to play a few hands of hearts with
my roommate. Unexpectedly, the
chair broke from under me and sent
me into a tirade. I trashed my living
quarters, releasing an unfurled rage

at everything that had gone wrong

for me that day.

Well, not really.

The whole scenario sounds
pretty stupid, don’t you think? The
excuse for it is even stupider. But
hey, for the U.S. Olympic hockey
team, anything goes. Well  not
exactly. V ,

After a heartbreaking loss to the
Czech Republic in Olympic hockey

7: competition, the U.S. team left the

rink disappointed, falling miles
away from its medal expectations.
The players disappointed them—
selves, USA Hockey, their respec-
tive NHL franchises and the United
States, and killed whatever hopes
the United States had of becoming
a world hockey powerhouse.

So after that fateful match, the
guys went nuts. In their frustration,
they happened to sit down for a
card game and break some ﬂimsy
chairs, which led to players
allegedly releasing fire extinguish-
ers on goaltender Mike Richter,
which then led to those same play-
ers allegedly shattering a window
-— a piece of which injured a
Canadian bobsledder.

The incident set off a media
frenzy of finger-pointing, name-
calling and flying whodunit accusa-
tions that would make even
Sherlock Holmes proud. But in the
genre of Sen. Joe McCarthy, the
affair has become a witch hunt.
Despite constant prodding and
pleading, the guilty parties won’t
confess.

And now Chris Chelios is sin-
gle-handedly trying to reestablish
the goodwill ties that were severed
between the United States and
Japan, the United States and the
International Olympic Committee,
USA Hockey and the IOC, the
National Hockey League and the
IOC, the United States and Canada
and any other organizations that
belong in this alphabet soup gone
horribly sour.

