COLUMN

Bad move, Chelly Boy.-

The U.S. team captain and
Chicago Blackhawk defenseman
stepped in as peacemaker and as
unofficial U.S. Olympic team
spokesman. He paid the entire
$3000 worth of damage to the
Olympic Village and issued an
apology on behalf of the U.S.
Olympic team. But he made himself
look like an even bigger fool.

The story goes something like
this:

My friend knew a girl in her
residence hall who put a container
of homemade ice cream in a com-

FROM PAGE 9

.mon—area refrigerator. The next day

this poor soul went to eat it but it
was gone. My friend wanted to
exercise her good nature and give
this person a tub of Ben and Jerry’s
because she felt bad for her, but I
told her not to do it.

The whole notion of nicely
replacing the ice cream said that
she was guilty. But she wasn’t.

Like that anecdote, the whole
notion of Chelios giving the IOC
$3000 in reparation might as well
scream that he is guilty, although
he probably isn’t. And whoever
those guilty parties really are, still
won’t confess. Sadly, they probably
never will.

If I ever trashed my room and
took no initiative to ‘fess up to my
crime, my mom would inflict
severe bodily and mental harm on
me until I told the truth.

And trust me, Mrs. Lenzi is not
a woman whose path you want to
cross.

Now I don’t know if Gary
Bettman, the head of USA Hockey,
or the head of the IOC have the
same temper and tolerance level
that my mom has, but there is talk
of banning the 23 players from any
future Olympic and international
competition, further tarnishing the
once-budding image of USA
Hockey.

But besides guilt, anger, and
embarrassment, the behaviorof the
U.S. hockey team was simply not
called for.

Even U.S. Head Coach Ron
Wilson said that the actions of the
guilty parties displayed “no class at
all.”

Parents teach their children to
respect others’ property. And in the
tradition of all antique shops and
flea markets, there is still the time-
honored tradition that if you break
it, you buy it.

And right now, broken furniture
is the least of USA Hockey’s wor-
ries.

Rachel Lenzi is a columnist for The
Pitt News.

